<font color="#FF0000">SONGS MY FATHER NEVER SANG</font><br>
<tt>Fri Aug 15 23:17:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Certain songs bring the period of training to go to Vietnam and my time over there back to my mind.  I see the worn down WWII vintage buildings of Fort Holabird or the tents of the 172nd MI Co in the dusty cul-de-sac within sight of the perimeter at LZ English.  For the first - the Stone Ponys album containing &quot;Different Drum and &quot;Love is Blue&quot; done by Paul Mauriat.  For the second - &quot;We Gotta Get out of This Place&quot; and &quot;It Must Be Him&quot; (sung by every female lead singer of the interchangeable Filipino rock bands that passed through every few weeks to the unwitting aggravation of guys who wanted to hear anything but).<br><br>
Then there was the music that wasn't there; though I was usuually to busy to notice.  No Dvorak, Grieg, Rimsky-Korsakov or Beethoven.  Permanently lost my &quot;lip&quot; for playing the French Horn.<br><br>
Lastly there was the music of the land; if you were fortunate enough to have the war's roar and racket quiet down without constant threat long enough to hear it.....especially the soft Spring breeze off the South China Sea sounding the greening strings of its ancient and ever new instrument, the newly transplanted rice seedlings.  And somewhere beyond my ears' hearing though sensed by my heart, the angels made heaven ring with the lush tones of russet and gold sunrises and salmon and magenta sunsets I can still see as if I were still there.  But I remember no music in the night for war stalked stealthily in the blackness, and everything strained to shut up and listen; unless it was the tinny drumming of the monsoon rains which knew neither day nor night. 
